Keir Starmer's "we need to return the sausages" is a very nostalgic gaffe, the type of mistake a Belgian politician makes in the 1960s and it gets written about on all the front pages of the newspapers. Far more civilized than Brandon's dementia babble you couldn't even laugh at.

The contrast of making a big speech about planetary political issues, wars where millions die, etc. but getting distracted because you're hungry and thinking forward to the kind of lunch you're about to have is inherently humorous, like a maestro pianist distracted by a mosquito.

The biggest difference between maritime life and life on land is everything is efficient on a ship. You don't have to waste time doing your laundry or cooking, there's a steward doing all of these menial tasks for you. You either work or rest. It's like a technocratic microstate.

My friend who's an officer on a ship says it's genuinely hard to adjust to having so much of your time just wasted with useless stuff like cleaning windows at your apartment, having to go pay bills and shop, you don't realize how inefficient it is until you experience life at sea
well if you're doing the laundry that's the job and you're still either working or resting, it's not like you have to man the bridge for 5 minutes a few time per day or anything
